Here is an example of how to automatically generate a table of contents in LaTeX:

\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
...
\section{Methods}
... 
\section{Results}
...
\section{Discussion}
...

\end{document}

The key points are:

- Include the \tableofcontents command where you want the table of contents to appear, usually at the beginning of the document.

- Use \section{} commands to divide the document into sections. 

- LaTeX will automatically gather the section titles and their page numbers and generate the table of contents.

- The table of contents will have links to the corresponding page numbers of the sections.

- Run LaTeX twice to ensure the page numbers are correct.

So in summary, LaTeX does the work automatically - you just need to structure the document into sections and tell LaTeX where to place the generated table of contents.

Here is LATEX code to draw a chessboard from a FEN notation:

\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}

\chessboard[setfen=r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 5 4]

\end{document}

The key points are:

- Include the chessboard package 

- Use the \chessboard command and specify the FEN notation with the setfen option

- The FEN notation defines the position of all pieces on the board

- The additional w KQkq - 5 4 at the end defines side to move (w = white), castling rights (KQkq means white can castle kingside and queenside, black kingside), en passant square (- means no en passant) and move number

So this will generate a chessboard with the position defined by the FEN string. The chessboard package handles drawing the board and pieces automatically.

